Security Operations Fundamentals > [T2]: Lab - OSSEC: Detect webshells

Detect webshells dropped in the apache root folder (FIM)

OSSEC comes pre-loaded with Out-Of-Box rules to check for SSH brute-force, watch specific directories, and even monitor kernel-loaded drivers.


To utilize one of the pre-defined rules, we will look at one already located in /var/ossec/rules/ossec_rules.xml.

Fire up your terminal, open /var/ossec/rules/local_rules.xml, then add your rule under <group name="local,syslog,"> section.

Figure - zoom in

 

Did you see that?! We just copied and then pasted the rule from ossec_rules.xml to local_rules.xml with a slight modification in the <rule> config.

All you need to do is to change the level from 0 to 11 and add overwrite="yes" 

FIM in OSSEC looks for pre-configured specific files and directories, so If we want to look for changes within the /var/www/html directory, we will need to modify /var/ossec/etc/ossec.conf to:

  • Include the new location within the <syscheck> section
  • Alert on new files by adding <alert_new_files>yes</alert_new_files>

Figure - zoom in

  • Restart OSSEC server: sudo systemctl restart ossec
  • Create a test file: sudo echo \(\$_GET[1]\) > /var/www/html/shell.php
  • Visit the OSSEC UI to see the result: http://127.0.0.1/ossec-wui/index.php
